        <name>Close</name>
        <onclick/>
        <order>600</order>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles>
        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    // Per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 6 (Resolved -> Closed):
    //   "Caller has x_casemgmt_case_manager role; auto-set closed_date"
    //   "Surface form-level error" on failure
    // Per AAP Section 0.7.1: blocking errors must appear on the form.
    // Per AAP Section 0.7.4: blocking-error messages must come from the
    //   single-source-of-truth Script Include (no inlined hardcoded
    //   error strings).
    //
    // This is the SERVER-side click handler for the Close form button.
    // It runs in the server sandbox (no window, has current GlideRecord,
    // has gs and action) and is responsible for:
    //   1) Defense-in-depth role re-check (must be case_manager).
    //   2) Defense-in-depth status re-check (must be 'Resolved').
    //   3) Delegation to the central Script Include's canTransitionToClosed
    //      method, which encapsulates the case_manager role guard AND
    //      the verbatim error message text.
    //   4) Status persistence (current.status = 'Closed'; current.update()).
    //      The cooperating set_closed_date Business Rule (order=500)
    //      fires on this update and auto-populates closed_date =
    //      gs.nowDateTime() before the database write completes.
    //   5) Form refresh (action.setRedirectURL(current)).
    //
    // Each of the three guards above maps to a row in the AAP Section
    // 0.5.6 ACL matrix or the AAP Section 0.5.5 transition map:
    //   - Guard 1: Role check enforces "Only case_manager can close
    //     cases" (case_agent and case_viewer are excluded per AAP
    //     Section 0.5.5 row 6 verbatim).
    //   - Guard 2: Status check enforces "Only Resolved -> Closed" (no
    //     other transition can fire this handler).
    //   - Guard 3: The Script Include's canTransitionToClosed check
    //     enforces the case_manager role per the AAP transition map;
    //     on failure it returns the verbatim "Only case managers can
    //     close cases." message.
    //
    // All three guards must pass before current.update() is called.
    // Any guard failure surfaces a blocking gs.addErrorMessage and
    // returns without persisting.

    // Guard 1: Role check. The user must hold case_manager.
    // The visibility <condition> and <roles> field already gate the
    // button on this role, but the server-side re-check protects
    // against the rare case where a user lost the role between form
    // load and form submit, and against attempts to invoke the
    // form-submit verb directly via Table API. The defensive role
    // re-check is the FIRST guard so that role-escalation attempts
    // surface a role-specific error rather than a status-specific
    // message that might leak workflow information.
    if (!gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager')) {
        gs.addErrorMessage('Only case managers can close cases.');
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // Guard 2: Status check. The case must currently be Resolved.
    // Re-checking on the server protects against a stale-form attack
    // where the user opens the form when status is Resolved, the
    // case transitions in another tab (e.g., another manager closes
    // it), then the user submits from the original tab. The check
    // uses string comparison against the verbatim Title Case
    // 'Resolved' label per AAP Section 0.5.7 (the choice value
    // defined in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml). Without the
    // defensive re-check, a stale-form click on an already-Closed
    // case would fail with the cryptic block_terminal_closed BR
    // error message, which while technically correct does not
    // educate the user about the underlying staleness. With this
    // re-check, the user receives an immediate and informative
    // blocking error: "Only Resolved cases can be closed."
    if (current.status != 'Resolved') {
        gs.addErrorMessage('Only Resolved cases can be closed.');
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // Guard 3: Transition guard. Delegate the role check to the
    // central Script Include - the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for both
    // the case_manager role check AND the verbatim error message
    // text, shared with the Flow Designer subflow
    // ../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml. Centralizing
    // the guard guarantees that:
    //   - The verbatim error message "Only case managers can close
    //     cases." is identical across all callers (no drift between
    //     this UI Action's surfaced message and the flow's surfaced
    //     message).
    //   - Future rule changes (e.g., requiring a closure_reason or
    //     adding a second precondition like "all parties must be
    //     associated") only need to be made in the Script Include.
    //   - The role membership check lives in only one place (the
    //     Script Include's canTransitionToClosed helper), avoiding
    //     duplication and ensuring consistent role-resolution
    //     semantics (current-user-by-default with explicit-userId
    //     branch for non-current-user contexts).
    //
    // The Script Include's canTransitionToClosed(caseGr, userId) method
    // returns:
    //   { ok: true } when the user has the case_manager role, OR
    //   { ok: false, error: 'Only case managers can close cases.' }
    //     when the role check fails (the VERBATIM message), OR
    //   { ok: false, error: 'Case record is missing.' } when caseGr
    //     is null/undefined (defensive guard against unexpected input).
    //
    // The userId parameter is gs.getUserID() (the current session
    // user); the Script Include's logic short-circuits to gs.getUser()
    // for current-user-by-default, which is the most efficient
    // role-membership-check path.
    //
    // The result.error string is surfaced VERBATIM via gs.addErrorMessage,
    // NOT replaced with a hardcoded UI-Action-local message. This
    // honors the agent prompt's Rule 5 ("Delegate to Script Include -
    // single source of truth") and Rule 6 ("Surface Errors via
    // gs.addErrorMessage() - Display the Script Include's result.error
    // on form").
    var validator = new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator();
    var result = validator.canTransitionToClosed(current, gs.getUserID());
    if (!result.ok) {
        gs.addErrorMessage(result.error);
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // All three guards passed. Perform the Resolved -> Closed
    // transition. The status assignment uses the verbatim Title Case
    // 'Closed' label per AAP Section 0.5.7 and the sibling choice
    // file ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml.
    //
    // The single current.update() call triggers the platform's full
    // before-update Business Rule pipeline, including:
    //   - block_terminal_closed (order=100, no-op for THIS update
    //     because previous.status is Resolved, not Closed; will
    //     PREVENT all subsequent updates after this one completes)
    //   - block_draft_backtransition (no-op, target is Closed not
    //     Draft)
    //   - validate_assigned_agent_membership (passes if assigned_agent
    //     is still a member of assigned_group; in normal workflow
    //     this should already be true when the case reached Resolved)
    //   - clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress (no-op, target is Closed
    //     not In Progress; pending_reason should already be empty
    //     since Resolved has no pending_reason)
    //   - set_closed_date (FIRES, order=500: target is Closed and
    //     previous is Resolved; auto-populates current.closed_date =
    //     gs.nowDateTime() before the database write completes - this
    //     is the AAP Section 0.5.5 row 6 "auto-set closed_date"
    //     side-effect)
    //
    // The two parent state-machine flows (general_inquiry_state_machine
    // and complaint_state_machine) ALSO fire on this update via their
    // OnUpdate triggers filtered on `status` change, calling the
    // validate_closed_transition subflow which itself delegates to
    // x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.canTransitionToClosed() -
    // the SAME helper this UI Action just called. Belt-and-suspenders
    // defense in depth.
    //
    // After this update completes, ANY future modification attempt
    // will be REJECTED by the block_terminal_closed BR (order=100)
    // with the verbatim AAP Section 0.7.4 message "Closed cases are
    // terminal and cannot be modified." This is the canonical
    // anti-regression guarantee that closure is irreversible.
    current.status = 'Closed';
    current.update();

    // Refresh the form to show the new status AND the auto-populated
    // closed_date stamp. The standard ServiceNow UI-Action pattern
    // is to call action.setRedirectURL(current) which navigates the
    // browser to the same record's form view, picking up the new
    // status and any side-effect field changes (e.g., closed_date
    // populated by set_closed_date BR; audit timestamps updated by
    // the platform's standard sys_* pipeline). After the refresh,
    // the form will display the case in Closed status with the
    // closed_date stamped to the current time.
    action.setRedirectURL(current);
})();]]></script>
